# Security Rules

Baseline security practices for every application. These are the defaults you should start with - adjust thresholds and specific techniques to your product's threat model. Apply the sections relevant to your project's technology. (See AGENTS.md Enforcement table for how to read MUST/NEVER language.)

> All numeric values (thresholds, sizes, timings, percentages) in this file are `[DEFAULT]` - adjust per project.

---

## Decision tests

### Audience test (responses)

Who receives this JSON? Maintain an **allowlist per audience** (admin, public, internal). Never use one serializer for all channels.

### Input test (mutations)

Parse body with the project's **shared schema** (Zod, Joi, etc.). Never spread raw client JSON into updates (mass-assignment / injection risk).

### Logging test

**Never** log secret values. **May** log actor id + correlation/request id + stack on server. See `logging.md`.

---

## Authentication Security

- **bcrypt** with cost factor `[DEFAULT]` 12+ for password hashing (NEVER MD5, SHA-1, SHA-256 alone, or plaintext)
- **Same client-visible text** for invalid credentials - never reveal which part of the credential pair failed (avoid account enumeration)
- **httpOnly cookies** for session tokens in web apps - preferred over localStorage/sessionStorage. Mobile apps and non-browser clients use secure storage (Keychain, EncryptedSharedPreferences) or short-lived tokens with rotation.
- **Secure flag** on cookies in production (HTTPS only)
- **SameSite=Lax** minimum on auth cookies (prevents most CSRF)
- **Token rotation** on privilege escalation (password change, role change)
- **Session invalidation** on credential change (kill all active sessions tied to the compromised or rotated secret)
- **Constant-time comparison** for tokens and hashes (prevent timing attacks)

---

## Rate Limiting

| Category | Limit `[DEFAULT]` | Window | Notes |
|----------|-------------------|--------|-------|
| High-sensitivity endpoints (credential checks, recovery-style flows, bulk sensitive mutations) | 5-10 attempts | 15 minutes | Optional parallel hourly cap where needed; CAPTCHA vs hard lockout on shared IPs; tune per flow |
| API (authenticated - standard) | 300 requests | 1 minute | Tune per workload - data-intensive or real-time endpoints often need higher ceilings |
| API (unauthenticated - public) | 30 requests | 1 minute | Raise or lower when exposing intentional public APIs |
| File upload | configurable per role | - | See file-media.md |

> These are **starting defaults**, not fixed values. Tune based on usage patterns, threat model, and client mix (consumer vs. enterprise networks, shared IPs, etc.).

- Rate limit by IP + identifier (email/user ID)
- Return `429 Too Many Requests` with `Retry-After` header
- Show user-friendly notice with wait time

