## Input Validation & Sanitization

- **Validate EVERYTHING server-side** - client validation is UX only, not security
- **Whitelist allowed values** - don't blacklist bad ones (always incomplete)
- **Trim and normalize** strings before validation
- **Limit string lengths** - set max length on all text inputs (prevent payload abuse)
- **Validate file types** by content (magic bytes), not just extension
- **Limit file sizes** (enforce both client and server side)
- **Reject unexpected fields** - only accept known properties
- **Type coercion** - ensure numbers are numbers, booleans are booleans
- **Sanitize HTML** in rich text inputs (strip script tags, event handlers)

---

## SQL Injection Prevention

- **ALWAYS use parameterized queries** / prepared statements
- **NEVER concatenate** user input into query strings
- **Use ORM/query builders** that auto-parameterize
- **Validate and type-cast** user-provided IDs before queries
- **Audit raw queries** - if you must write raw SQL, review it for injection

---

## XSS Prevention

- **Escape all output** by default (most frameworks do this)
- **Content Security Policy** header - restrict script sources

**Principle:** Never bind user-controlled data to raw HTML rendering APIs. Use your framework's safe rendering by default.

[REFERENCE] Common dangerous bindings by framework:

- **Never bind unsanitized user content** to raw HTML rendering (e.g. `innerHTML` in DOM, `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` in React, `v-html` in Vue)
- **Always sanitize** user-generated HTML before rendering (use a vetted sanitizer appropriate to your platform) - sanitized content in raw HTML rendering is acceptable for rich text editors, CMS content, etc.
- **HttpOnly** cookies prevent session theft even if XSS exists
- **X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff** header

---

## CSRF Prevention

- **SameSite cookies** (Lax or Strict) - first line of defense
- **CSRF tokens** for forms if SameSite isn't sufficient (legacy browser support)
- **Check Origin/Referer header** on state-changing requests
- **Custom header requirement** for API calls (X-Requested-With) - browsers won't send these cross-origin

---

## Client Data Path (MUST)

When the product has a browser client that talks to your backend:

- **Browser clients call your API (+ identity provider for login) only** - never vendor APIs, database drivers, Redis, or internal service URLs directly from the bundle.
- **Secrets and vendor keys live on the server/workers** - env vars, secret managers, or server-only config. Nothing sensitive in client env vars that ship to the browser.
- **Server validates and proxies** - if the UI needs third-party data (headlines, link previews, AI chat), the API fetches or forwards it; the browser never holds vendor credentials.
- **Authorization before data** - privileged content (paid tiers, admin-only fields, role-gated resources) is enforced on the server on every request, not hidden-only in UI.

Document the allowed client origins and API base URL in `docs/setup.md` and `.env.example`.

---

## Multi-Origin Frontends (When Applicable)

Not every project splits app and admin across domains. **Ask at project start** (see `feature-discovery.md` § New Project Bootstrap).

When the product has **separate browser apps on separate origins** (e.g. trader app + admin app + API):

- **Separate origins** - prefer distinct subdomains or domains over path-only separation when apps have different audiences and cookie scopes.
- **Separate auth clients** - each SPA gets its own OAuth/OIDC app client (or equivalent) when the identity provider supports it.
- **CORS allowlist** - API allows only the known frontend origins; never `*` on authenticated routes.
- **Cookies and CSP** - configure per origin; do not share session cookies across unrelated apps unless explicitly designed.
- **Privileged routes** - role gates enforced server-side on every API call, not UI-only hide.

---

## CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing)

- **Explicit origins only** - never `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *` on authenticated APIs
- **Whitelist specific domains** that should access your API
- **Limit methods** - only allow methods your API actually uses
- **Limit headers** - only expose headers the client actually needs
- **Credentials: true** only for origins that need cookie-based auth

---

## Security Headers (Set on All Responses)

Every web application should set security headers. The **specific values depend on your app** (CDNs, third-party scripts, iframe requirements, API integrations), but every project should explicitly configure:

**Principle:** Set security headers that prevent common browser-based attacks. The specific headers depend on your platform and deployment.

[REFERENCE] Common security headers for web applications:

| Header | Purpose | Notes |
|--------|---------|-------|
| `X-Content-Type-Options` | Prevent MIME-type sniffing | Typically `nosniff` |
| `X-Frame-Options` | Control iframe embedding | `DENY` or `SAMEORIGIN` based on your needs |
| `Strict-Transport-Security` | Force HTTPS | Set `max-age` and `includeSubDomains` per your domain setup |
| `Content-Security-Policy` | Restrict script/style/resource sources | **Project-specific** - depends on CDNs, inline scripts, third-party embeds. Start restrictive, widen as needed. |
| `Referrer-Policy` | Control referrer leakage | Choose based on your privacy needs |
| `Permissions-Policy` | Restrict browser features (camera, mic, etc.) | Deny everything you don't use |

**Rules:**
- **Define headers per project** - never copy-paste a CSP from another project; each app has different third-party integrations and inline requirements
- **Start restrictive, then widen** - deny by default, add exceptions as needed
- **Test headers after every deploy** that changes resource sources (new CDN, new analytics script, etc.)
- **Disable `X-XSS-Protection`** (set to `0`) - rely on CSP instead; the legacy filter causes its own vulnerabilities

---

## Data Exposure Prevention

- **Never expose** internal IDs if they reveal information (use UUIDs or opaque tokens for public-facing)
- **Never expose** stack traces, file paths, or server versions in error responses
- **Never expose** database field names that reveal schema structure
- **Never expose** other users' data without explicit permission check
- **Never log** passwords, tokens, sensitive data (PII, secrets, recovery artifacts), or full credential material
- **Redact sensitive fields** in audit logs

---

## File Upload Security

- **Validate MIME type** by reading file header (magic bytes), not just extension
- **Rename files** - never use user-provided filenames as-is
- **Store outside web root** - files shouldn't be directly accessible
- **Scan for malware** on upload (use a scanning solution appropriate for your infrastructure)
- **Limit file size** (server rejects before full upload if possible)
- **Restrict allowed types** - whitelist specific MIME types

---

## Environment & Configuration

- **Never commit secrets** - use environment variables or secret managers
- **Different secrets** per environment (dev/staging/prod)
- **.env files** in .gitignore (provide .env.example with dummy values)
- **Rotate secrets** periodically (API keys, JWT secrets)
- **Audit access** - know who has access to production secrets

---

## Dependency Security

**Principle:** Treat dependencies as attack surface. Keep them updated, minimal, and audited.

[REFERENCE] Dependency security checklist:

- **Keep dependencies updated** - check for vulnerabilities regularly
- **Audit tools** - use your ecosystem's vulnerability scanner (e.g. `npm audit`, `pip audit`, `bundler-audit`, Dependabot, or equivalent)
- **Lock files** - commit package-lock.json / yarn.lock / Pipfile.lock
- **Minimal dependencies** - every dependency is an attack surface
- **Review major updates** before applying (check changelogs for breaking changes)

