## Session Verification Pattern

Every backend with authentication should have a **single session verification function**:

```
function getVerifiedSession():
  -> Extract token from cookie/header
  -> Verify signature (JWT) or lookup session in DB
  -> Load user record (confirm still active)
  -> Return typed user object OR null
```

- Called as the **first line** of every protected API route
- Returns a strongly-typed user object (not `any`)
- A single source of truth - never duplicate this logic across handlers

---

## Authorization / Permission Pattern

IF your project has role-based access control (RBAC) or permissions:

**Principle:** Centralize permission definitions and checks. Every permission check in the app should reference a single source of truth.

[REFERENCE] Example file/module layout (framework-specific):

```
Structure:
  permissions.shared    -> Types, keys, constants (importable by BOTH client and server)
  permissions           -> Server-only logic (DB lookups, hierarchy resolution, scope filters)
  usePermissions        -> Client hook/context (loads permissions, exposes hasPermission())

Rules:
  - Permission keys are typed constants (not magic strings) - shared between client and server
  - Server checks are the authority (client checks are for UX only - hide/show UI)
  - Every API handler checks permissions AFTER authentication, BEFORE execution
  - Reusable helper: hasPermission(actor, "resource:action") -> boolean
  - Scope-aware: some permissions apply to "own" data, others to "all" data - handle both
```

---

## Secure Time-Limited Token Handling

When implementing **any** one-time or short-lived token (recovery, verification, magic link, invite, etc.):

1. Generate a **cryptographically random** token (sufficient entropy, e.g. `[DEFAULT]` 32+ random bytes) - use your language's CSPRNG (e.g. `crypto.randomBytes` in Node, `secrets` in Python)
2. Store the **hash** of the token in the database (never store raw)
3. Deliver the **raw** token to the recipient through your chosen channel (e.g. signed deep link, out-of-band delivery) - never log the raw value
4. On verification: hash the submitted token, compare to stored hash (constant-time)
5. **One-time use** - delete/invalidate the token after successful use
6. **Expiry** - token expires after `[DEFAULT]` 1 hour (tune per risk)
7. On successful redemption for a **credential or account change**: invalidate ALL existing sessions for that principal (force fresh authentication everywhere)

